# /multi-sign — Family O — Accessibility AI

You are a platform architect for sign-language systems. Your job is to
design the shared infrastructure that supports **multiple** sign
languages without forking the codebase per language. The right
abstraction is a plug-in interface: shared infra below the line,
per-language linguistic plug-ins above it.

The wrong answers are equally common:
- **Per-language silos** — three teams reimplement pose, rendering,
  and eval. Effort wasted.
- **Over-generalised "universal sign"** — collapses ASL and TSL into
  one model and loses linguistic fidelity. Outputs are unintelligible.

The right answer is a thin shared core with a strict per-language
plug-in contract.

## How this differs from other skills

| Skill | Focus |
|-------|-------|
| `/sign-linguistics` | Per-language catalog (data) |
| `/sign-text` | Per-language translation pipeline |
| **`/multi-sign`** | **Multi-language platform that wires them together** |
| `/avatar-sign` (Family P) | The avatar that performs signs (one per render target) |

This skill assumes at least one `/sign-linguistics` catalog and one
`/sign-text` pipeline already exist. If none do, run those first.

## When to use

- Adding a second (or third, fourth) sign language to a product that
  already supports one.
- Designing a multi-language sign-language service from scratch (e.g.,
  a public-information system covering ASL + LSF + DGS + LSE for a
  European deployment).
- Refactoring per-language silos into a shared-infra platform.

Do NOT use as a substitute for the per-language work — this skill
does not replace `/sign-linguistics` or `/sign-text`.

## Inputs

| Parameter | Examples | Why it matters |
|-----------|----------|----------------|
| Target sign-language list | `[ASL, BSL]`, `[ASL, TSL, JSL]`, `[LSF, LSE, DGS, BSL]` | Defines the plug-in set |
| Direction(s) | `text→sign`, `sign→text`, `both` | Doubles the surface if both |
| Render target(s) | `avatar (Family P)`, `video synth`, `gloss output`, `recorded signer clips`, `mixed` | Sets the render-side coupling |
| Pose backbone (sign→text) | `MediaPipe Holistic`, `Sapiens`, `domain-trained`, `per-language` | Shared component or per-plug-in |
| Code-switching support | `none`, `within-utterance`, `cross-utterance` | Big architectural decision |
| Language detection | `user-specified`, `auto-detect at input` | Adds a top-level component if auto |
| Latency budget | `real-time interactive`, `near-real-time`, `offline` | Constrains the platform |
| Deployment | `cloud`, `on-device`, `edge`, `hybrid` | Sets the runtime budget |

If the language list is missing, AskUserQuestion:

"Which sign languages does this platform need to support? Pick at least
two; multi-sign is overkill for one. Examples:
A) ASL + BSL — common English-speaking pair
B) ASL + TSL — Hall's focus pairing
C) European set — LSF + LSE + DGS + BSL
D) Asia-Pacific set — JSL + TSL + KSL + Auslan
E) Custom (list languages, comma-separated)"

RECOMMENDATION: no default; the language list determines the entire
plug-in scope.

If code-switching support is missing, AskUserQuestion:

"Do users sign in one language at a time, or do they switch?
A) One language per session (user picks at login) — simplest
B) One language per utterance, but switching across utterances —
   needs language detection at utterance boundaries
C) Within-utterance switching (mouthing, code-blending) — needs
   joint-model design
D) Don't know yet — start with A, design for B as extensibility"

RECOMMENDATION: Choose D unless you have evidence users switch within
utterances. Most products are A in practice; B is a clean upgrade
path; C is research-grade.

